ch 1936","1285":"1285","1350":"1350","1271":"1271","about 1285":"about 1285","Loddekopinge,Harjager,Malmohus,Sweden":"Löddeköpinge, Harjager, Malmöhus, Sweden","Denmark":"Denmark","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: relationship name from the Middle English personal name  <i>Tot(te)</i> (Old English  <i>Totta</i>,  <i>Tota</i>).  See also  Totty  ,   Tutt  , and compare Sabyna Tottedoghter’, 1379 in   Poll Tax   (Kirkby Malham, WR Yorks); Radulphus Totusone, 1377 in   Poll Tax   (Frisby on the Wreak, Leics). Some early bearers may belong with (2) or (3).","2  English: nickname from Middle English  <i>tot(te)</i> ‘simpleton, fool’.","3  English: locative name from Middle English  <i>tot(e)</i> ‘lookout hill’ (Old English  <i>tōt(e)</i>). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on or by a lookout hill, or toponymic, for someone from a place so named, such as Toat Farm in Pulborough (Sussex) and Toat Hill in Slinfold (Sussex).  Compare  Toothill  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Toothill","meanings":["English: (i) locative name from various places named with Old English * <i>tōt-hyll</i> ‘lookout hill’, primarily Toothill in Rastrick (WR Yorks) and perhaps Tootle in Longridge (Lancs), but also Tuttle Hill in Nuneaton (Warwicks), and Tothill (Lincs). There are several further minor place-names of this type that may have contributed to the surname. (ii) locative name, occasionally from Tottenhill (Norfolk), recorded as  <i>Totehill</i> in 1251."]},{"name":"Poll Tax","meanings":["English: locative name, a rationalization of the place-name  <i>Chideock</i> (Dorset), now pronounced /'tʃidik/. Johannes Chidiok, 1377 in   Poll Tax   (Leaden Roding, Essex) shows that people of this name moved east in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Tutt","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Tut(te)</i> (Old English <i>Tutta</i>). Compare   Tutty  . The Old English personal name is preserved in various placenames, including Tutnall (Worcestershire) and Tuttington (Norfolk).","English: variant of   Tout   and perhaps also of <b>Tott</b>, which derives from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Tot(te)</i>, representing either Old English <i>Tot(t)a</i> (of uncertain origin) or Old Norse <i>Tóti</i>, which is probably a pet form of Old Norse <i>Thorsteinn</i>.","German (also <b>Tütt</b>): from a short form of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with the ancient Germanic element <i>theud</i> ‘people, tribe’ (see   Dietrich  ), or from a short form of <i>Dudo</i>, originally a name from nursery talk."]},{"name":"Tot","meanings":["Croatian, Slovenian, and Serbian; Rusyn and Slovak (from Vojvodina in Serbia): from <i>Tot</i>, an ethnic name of Hungarian origin (see   Toth   1), denoting either a Croat of the Kajkavian language or a Slovenian or a Slovak living in the regions which were part of Hungary before WWI.","Amerindian (Guatemala): Mayan name, from a word denoting a snail.","East African (South Sudan): unexplained."]},{"name":"Tote","meanings":["English:  see  Tott  ."]},{"name":"Totts","meanings":["English: variant of   Tott   with post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Totty","meanings":["English:","perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Tot(t)i</i>, a variant of <i>Tot(t)e</i>, representing either Old English <i>Tot(t)a</i> (of uncertain origin) or Old Scandinavian <i>Tóti</i>, which is probably a pet form of Old Scandinavian <i>Thorsteinn</i>.","nickname from Middle English <i>toti</i> ‘dizzy, unsteady, befuddled’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1353273,"age":79,"year":"1350","julianDay":2214138,"description":"Plague ravishes Denmark and Sweden.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Botildie Tott was born in 1271, in Denmark. She had at least 2 sons with Tord Aagesen Thott."},"et":{"1271–":"1271–Surnud","1268–1301":"1268–1301","1285–13